Berlin Borough Survey: CPA vs CPM Source Comparison

January 29, 2026

Executive Summary

This report compares two identical Berlin borough surveys sourced differently: CPA (Cost Per Acquisition) vs CPM (Cost Per Mille / impression-based). Both used the same questionnaire; the only difference is respondent sourcing method.

Weighting dimensions (Berlin-wide ANES raking): Age \(\times\) Gender (6 cells), Education (ISCED 5+ vs Rest), and Borough (12 districts). BTW 2025 vote recall is not used as a weighting variable it is shown for comparison only.

  • CPA: 335 valid Berlin adults from 574 responses (58% yield). Design effect 2.29, effective n = 146.
  • CPM: 204 valid Berlin adults from 333 responses (61% yield). Design effect 2.08, effective n = 98.

Sample and Weighting Diagnostics

Metric CPA CPM

Yield (%) 58% 61%

Design effect 2.29 2.08
Effective n 146 98
Weight CV 1.14 1.04

Interpretation: A higher design effect means the weighting had to do more work to correct sample imbalances, which reduces effective sample size. A design effect of 1.0 would mean no correction was needed.
